ଭୁବନେଶ୍ୱର: ନବନିଯୁକ୍ତ ଓଡ଼ିଶା ଟାକ୍ସେସନ୍ ଏବଂ ଆକାଉଣ୍ଟସ ସର୍ଭିସ୍&zwnj; (ଓଟିଏସ୍&zwnj;) ଅଧିକାରୀ ଭୀମସେନ ଟୁଡୁଙ୍କ ଉପରେ ରାଜ୍ୟ ସରକାର କଡ଼ା କାର୍ଯ୍ୟାନୁଷ୍ଠାନ ନେଇଛନ୍ତି। ମୁଖ୍ୟମନ୍ତ୍ରୀ ମୋହନ ଚରଣ ମାଝୀ ଆଜି ତାଙ୍କୁ ସରକାରୀ ଚାକିରିରୁ ବହିଷ୍କାର କରିଛନ୍ତି। ଏହାସହ ଶ୍ରୀ ଟୁଡୁ ଭବିଷ୍ୟତରେ ବି ଆଉ କୌଣସି ସରକାରୀ ଚାକିରି ପାଇବା ପାଇଁ ଯୋଗ୍ୟ ବିବେଚିତ ହେବେ ନାହିଁ ବୋଲି କୁହାଯାଇଛି।
Odisha STF ganja raid, ମାସେ ଧରି ଚାଲିଥିଲା ଅପରେସନ୍&zwnj; &lsquo;ଗ୍ରିନ୍&zwnj; କ୍ଲିନ୍&zwnj;&rsquo;, ଶେଷରେ ଗିରଫ ହେଲା ଆନ୍ତଃରାଜ୍ୟ ଗଞ୍ଜେଇ କାରବାରର କିଙ୍ଗ୍&zwnj;ପିନ୍&zwnj;
ଚନ୍ଦ୍ରିକା ମୃତ୍ୟୁ ମାମଲାରେ ମୁଖ୍ୟମନ୍ତ୍ରୀଙ୍କ ଦୃଢ଼ କାର୍ଯ୍ୟାନୁଷ୍ଠାନଭବିଷ୍ୟତରେ ବି ଆଉ ସରକାରୀ ଚାକିରି ପାଇଁ ଯୋଗ୍ୟ ହେବେନି
ସୂଚନାଯୋଗ୍ୟ୍ୟ, ନୂଆ କରି ଓଟିଏସ୍&zwnj; ପାଇଥିବା ଶ୍ରୀ ଟୁଡୁ ତାଙ୍କ ଇଣ୍ଡକ୍ସନ୍ ଟ୍ରେନିଂ ସମୟରେ ଜୁନ୍ ୪, ୨୦୨୬ରୁ ଅନୁପସ୍ଥିତ ଥିଲେ। ମଧୁସୂଦନ ଦାସ ରିଜିଓନାଲ୍ ଏକାଡେମି ଅଫ୍ ଫାଇନାନ୍ସିଆଲ୍ ମ୍ୟାନେଜମେଣ୍ଟରେ ତାଙ୍କ ଶେଷ ପରୀକ୍ଷାରେ ମଧ୍ୟ ସେ ଯୋଗ ଦେଇନଥିଲେ। ସେହି ସମୟରେ ସେ ଏକ ମୃତ୍ୟୁ ମାମଲାରେ ବାରଙ୍ଗ ପୁଲିସ ଦ୍ୱାରା ଗିରଫ ହୋଇଥିଲେ ଏବଂ ତାଙ୍କୁ ବିଚାର ବିଭାଗୀୟ ହାଜତକୁ ପଠାଯାଇଛି। ଆପରାଧିକ ମାମଲାରେ ୪୮ ଘଣ୍ଟାରୁ ଅଧିକ ସମୟ ଧରି ପୁଲିସ ଦ୍ୱାରା ଅଟକ ଥିବାରୁ ଆଇନ ଅନୁଯାୟୀ ତାଙ୍କୁ ସିଧାସଳଖ ସରକାରୀ ସେବାରୁ ବରଖାସ୍ତ କରାଯାଇଛି ବୋଲି କୁହାଯାଇଛି।&nbsp;
Odisha LED Street Light Scam ଏଲ୍&zwnj;ଇଡି ଷ୍ଟ୍ରିଟ୍&zwnj; ଲାଇଟ୍&zwnj; ଦୁର୍ନୀତି: କେନ୍ଦୁଝର, ନୟଗଡ଼ା ଓ ଯାଜପୁରରୁ ୩ ଠିକାଦାର ଗିରଫ
ଡାକ୍ତରୀ ଛାତ୍ରୀ ଚନ୍ଦ୍ରିକା ମୃତ୍ୟୁ ମାମଲାରେ ତାଙ୍କ ପ୍ରେମିକ ଭୀମସେନଙ୍କ ସମ୍ପୃକ୍ତି ଥିବା ନେଇ ଚନ୍ଦ୍ରିକାଙ୍କ ପରି&zwnj;ବାର ଲୋକ ଅଭିଯୋଗ କରିଥିଲେ। ପୁଲିସ ତଦନ୍ତ ସମୟରେ ଭୀମସେନଙ୍କର ଏହି ମୃତ୍ୟୁ ମାମଲାରେ ସଂପୃକ୍ତି ଥିବା ଜଣାପଡ଼ିଥିଲା। ଏହା ପରେ ମୁଖ୍ୟମନ୍ତ୍ରୀ କଡ଼ା କାର୍ଯ୍ୟାନୁଷ୍ଠାନ ନେଇଛନ୍ତି।

Shabir Hussain Khan &ndash; &lsquo;Blood Man of Kashmir&rsquo; &ndash; donates 194 pints, organises 1,200 camps; Humanity above everything, says Sajad Hussain
Srinagar/Budgam, Jun 27: In a world often divided by differences, two men from Kashmir have spent decades quietly proving that humanity still flows strongest through compassion.
For Shabir Hussain Khan of Srinagar, blood donation is not merely an act of charity&mdash;it is a lifelong mission to save lives, inspire society and build a culture of compassion and discipline among youth. Known widely as the &ldquo;Blood Man of Kashmir&rdquo;, Khan has donated an astonishing 194 pints of blood and has organised more than 1,200 blood donation camps across Jammu and Kashmir over the years.
Yet, despite the recognition, Khan says the true pain and struggle behind blood donation are only understood by those families who desperately search for blood during emergencies.
&ldquo;There are many blood donors in Kashmir, but only those who have suffered and faced difficult situations understand its real value,&rdquo; Khan told Rising Kashmir. &ldquo;During accidents, surgeries and medical emergencies, a single unit of blood can save an entire family from heartbreak.&rdquo;
Khan believes Kashmir urgently needs a stronger and more organised blood donation network, particularly for rare blood groups such as O-negative and B-negative, which are often difficult to arrange during emergencies.
&ldquo;We need online donor systems where blood donors are available just a click away. Plasma donors and rare blood group donors should be easily accessible to hospitals and patients,&rdquo; he said.
He stressed that blood donation should become a social movement rooted in awareness, discipline and regular medical screening.
&ldquo;Blood donors should increase day by day. A healthy society is one where people voluntarily come forward to save lives without expecting anything in return,&rdquo; Khan added.
Equally inspiring is the journey of Sajad Hussain from Magam in central Kashmir&rsquo;s Budgam district, whose blood donation journey began nearly four decades ago in 1987 after a neighbour&rsquo;s mother urgently required blood.
&ldquo;That was my first blood donation point,&rdquo; Sajad recalled. &ldquo;I saw a family in distress and realised that humanity is above everything else.&rdquo;
Since then, Sajad has donated around&nbsp;100 blood pints and continues to remain&nbsp;active in blood donation awareness campaigns across Kashmir.
&ldquo;This service is for humanity irrespective of religion, caste, creed or gender,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;The spirit of helping others is deeply connected with the teachings and sacrifice of Hazrat Imam Hussain (AS), who stood for humanity, compassion and justice.&rdquo;
Sajad believes awareness about blood donation must begin at the school level so that future generations grow up understanding its importance.
&ldquo;I urge Education Minister Sakeena Itoo and the Director School Education to include lessons about blood donation in the syllabus from Class 5 onwards,&rdquo; he said.
According to him, educational institutions can play a transformative role in creating socially responsible citizens who are prepared to help others during emergencies.
He called upon media organisations and social media influencers to actively promote voluntary blood donation campaigns.
&ldquo;The media has a huge responsibility. Social media can especially motivate thousands of young people. Youth must come forward and donate blood to save lives,&rdquo; he said.
Doctors and healthcare workers say voluntary blood donors remain the backbone of emergency healthcare systems, especially in regions vulnerable to accidents, surgeries and medical crises.
As Kashmir continues to witness rising road accidents and increasing healthcare needs, the stories of Shabir Hussain Khan and Sajad Hussain stand as powerful reminders that saving lives does not always require wealth or power&mdash;sometimes, it simply requires the willingness to give a part of oneself for another human being.
